Electric Vehicles data analysis¶

Xinzhao You

https://xinzhaoy.github.io/cmps6790_project/

Introduction:¶

Interest in electric vehicles (EVs) is growing. To gain a comprehensive understanding of the electric vehicle landscape, I aimed to explore three key data sets using Washington state as an example: electric vehicle ownership data, population and housing statistics, and alternative fuel stations.

Datasets¶

The following two datasets have all the necessary information I need in order to build prediction model and quantify discrimination in credit card application. I also provided descriptions of two datasets as well as how I am going to use them.

  • Dataset 1: Electric Vehicle Population Data

    https://data.wa.gov/Transportation/Electric-Vehicle-Population-Data/f6w7-q2d2

    This dataset shows the Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs) and Plug-in Hybrid Electric Vehicles (PHEVs) that are currently registered through Washington State Department of Licensing (DOL).

    Question: How have electric vehicle registrations evolved over the years, and are there discernible regional trends or hotspots?

  • Dataset 2: Alternative Fueling Stations from U.S. Department of Transportation

    https://data-usdot.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/usdot::alternative-fueling-stations/about

    Question: How does the availability of alternative fuel stations correlate with electric vehicle ownership?

  • Dataset 3: 2020 Census data

    https://ofm.wa.gov/washington-data-research/population-demographics/decennial-census/2020-census-everyone-counts/2020-census-what-you-need-know/2020-census-data-releases

    The apportionment population represents the first official 2020 Census numbers released by the U.S. Census Bureau.

    Question: What is the relationship between population/housing density and electric vehicle ownership?

Collaboration Plan¶

There is no collaboration plan because this is a solo project

# EV Registrations by County Over the Years
# Convert 'Model Year' to numeric
ev_table['Model Year'] = pd.to_numeric(ev_table['Model Year'], errors='coerce')
ev_table = ev_table[ev_table['Model Year'] >= 2008]
# Group by 'County' and 'Model Year' and count the registrations
ev_registrations = ev_table.groupby(['County', 'Model Year']).size().reset_index(name='Registrations')

# Pivot the table to have 'Model Year' as columns and 'County' as rows
ev_registrations_pivot = ev_registrations.pivot(index='County', columns='Model Year', values='Registrations').fillna(0)

# Plot the data
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
for county in ev_registrations_pivot.index:
    plt.plot(ev_registrations_pivot.columns, ev_registrations_pivot.loc[county], label=county)

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('EV Registrations')
plt.title('EV Registrations by County Over the Years')
plt.legend(title='County', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.xticks(ev_registrations_pivot.columns, rotation=45)
plt.show()

The chart demonstrates significant growth in EV registrations over time, particularly in King county that stands out with a steep increase. King County is following an exponential growth pattern, especially noticeable after 2020. The other counties show more gradual increases.

Model¶

  • Idea 1: Predicting EV Sataion by County build a model to predict the number of electric vehicle (EV) registrations in a county based on demographic and infrastructural factors. The model will consider variables such as total population, population density, number of housing units, and the presence of alternative fueling stations.

    The hypothesis suggests that counties with larger populations, higher population densities, and increased numbers of electric vehicle (EV) registrations are likely to have a greater number of EV charging stations constructed in those areas.

  • Idea 2: Correlation Between Population Metrics and EV Ownership investigate the correlation between population metrics and electric vehicle (EV) ownership. Specifically, it will examine how population size, population density, and housing characteristics within a county relate to the number of registered EVs.

    The hypothesis is that counties with larger populations and higher population densities may exhibit higher rates of EV ownership. Additionally, the availability of housing and the proportion of occupied versus vacant housing units might also influence EV adoption rates.
